WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:19.140
&gt;&gt;&gt; Good morning, ladies and gentlemen, and
welcome. At this time, please take your seats.

00:00:19.140 --> 00:00:39.740
We shall begin in two minutes. We shall begin
in two minutes. At this time, as a courtesy

00:00:39.740 --> 00:00:50.106
to our presenters, please make sure your cell
phones and any and all mobile devices are

00:00:50.106 --> 00:00:51.106
turned off at this time.
Thank you, good morning, and welcome. Please

00:00:51.106 --> 00:00:52.106
take your seats.
(Pause).

00:00:52.106 --> 00:00:53.106
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;&gt; Ladies and gentlemen, please welcome senior

00:00:53.106 --> 00:00:56.390
vice president, engineering, Vic Gundotra.
[ Applause ]

00:00:56.390 --> 00:01:04.150
[ Cheers and applause ]
&gt;&gt;Vic Gundotra: Well, good morning.

00:01:04.150 --> 00:01:09.380
Looks like you're all very excited to be here.
Welcome to Google I/O.

00:01:09.380 --> 00:01:14.329
[ Cheers and applause ]
&gt;&gt;Vic Gundotra: You know, this year marks

00:01:14.329 --> 00:01:18.999
our fourth year of this conference. And we
thought we'd begin by just reminiscing for

00:01:18.999 --> 00:01:22.319
a few moments about how much we have accomplished
together.

00:01:22.319 --> 00:01:27.920
You know, you go back to 2008. That was the
first year we held Google I/O. Maybe some

00:01:27.920 --> 00:01:30.810
of you were there at our inaugural conference.
[ Applause ]

00:01:30.810 --> 00:01:37.459
&gt;&gt;Vic Gundotra: That year, our opening keynote
focused on client, connectivity, and the cloud.

00:01:37.459 --> 00:01:42.189
Why, we recognized that this industry was
going through dramatic change, that mobile

00:01:42.189 --> 00:01:47.899
phones, smartphones, and faster Web browsers
were changing the face of clients, and that

00:01:47.899 --> 00:01:52.810
connectivity was about to explode, both in
its availability, as well as its bandwidth.

00:01:52.810 --> 00:01:57.369
And that would allow us to build cloud-based
services that we could hardly have dreamed

00:01:57.369 --> 00:02:05.270
of a few years ago. All that happened.
In 2009, on this stage, we rallied the industry

00:02:05.270 --> 00:02:11.920
with the Chrome team to move the Web forward
under the banner of HTML5. And today, modern

00:02:11.920 --> 00:02:17.470
browsers are better and faster because of
the work of this group of people.

00:02:17.470 --> 00:02:21.140
So thank you.
And then who could forget last year, when

00:02:21.140 --> 00:02:24.410
we focused --
[ Laughter ]

00:02:24.410 --> 00:02:34.700
&gt;&gt;Vic Gundotra: That was a lot of fun. And
we want to thank all of you for making Android

00:02:34.700 --> 00:02:40.580
the global phenomenon that it has become.
Of course, like Android, this conference,

00:02:40.580 --> 00:02:46.180
too, has gone truly global. We're very excited
about the 5,000-plus people that are in this

00:02:46.180 --> 00:02:51.940
room. But this year, for the first time, we
did something new. We created viewing parties.

00:02:51.940 --> 00:02:57.880
We allowed developers to set up their own
viewing parties and stream this event live.

00:02:57.880 --> 00:03:03.330
And we have over 110 cities that have these
viewing parties set up.

00:03:03.330 --> 00:03:08.140
On the screen behind me at any moment, we
should get a sampling of what's going on around

00:03:08.140 --> 00:03:13.200
the world live right now.
We have viewing parties in these 122 cities,

00:03:13.200 --> 00:03:19.670
including places like Cairo, where we have
over 1,000 people. It's 2:00 a.m. in the morning

00:03:19.670 --> 00:03:25.030
in Cairo.
[ Cheers and applause ]

00:03:25.030 --> 00:03:32.710
&gt;&gt;Vic Gundotra: And so to the more than 10,000
people at the viewing parties and the many,

00:03:32.710 --> 00:03:39.290
many thousands who are watching, who are watching
on YouTube, welcome to our conference.

00:03:39.290 --> 00:03:44.680
We're truly humbled by this worldwide enthusiasm.
We do recognize that you are sharing with

00:03:44.680 --> 00:03:50.460
us your most precious resource, your time.
And so we hope the next two days are incredibly

00:03:50.460 --> 00:03:55.010
valuable, exciting, and a lot of fun for all
of you.

00:03:55.010 --> 00:04:00.790
So let's get this show started. And to do
that, I'd like to introduce Hugo Barra, director

00:04:00.790 --> 00:04:04.730
of Android product management, to kick off
the opening keynote.

00:04:04.730 --> 00:04:08.720
Hugo.
[ Applause ]

00:04:08.720 --> 00:04:20.600
&gt;&gt;Hugo Barra: Well, good morning, everyone,
and welcome to the Android keynote at I/O

00:04:20.600 --> 00:04:25.320
2011.
Today, we have three things to talk to you

00:04:25.320 --> 00:04:33.320
about: Momentum, mobile, and more.
Let's start with momentum. And I'll ask you

00:04:33.320 --> 00:04:38.690
to follow me back in time for just one minute.
Do you guys remember this device?

00:04:38.690 --> 00:04:43.960
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Hugo Barra: Of course you do.

00:04:43.960 --> 00:04:49.760
Well, this is the T*Mobile G1, the very first
phone we shipped over two and a half years

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:57.430
ago. And it holds a special place in our hearts.
Back then, there were many skeptics. What

00:04:57.430 --> 00:05:03.570
did Google know? We had never been in the
mobile space or the operating system business.

00:05:03.570 --> 00:05:10.150
Well, from those humble beginnings of one
device and one carrier and one country, how

00:05:10.150 --> 00:05:14.350
much progress have we made?
We have so many exciting news to share with

00:05:14.350 --> 00:05:17.960
you today. So we made a quick video for you.
Let's have a look.

00:05:17.960 --> 00:05:37.050
[ Video. ]
[ Applause ]

00:05:37.050 --> 00:06:00.449
&gt;&gt;Hugo Barra: That's right. We're incredibly
thrilled to share with you today that we have

00:06:00.449 --> 00:06:05.320
activated over 100 million Android devices
worldwide.

00:06:05.320 --> 00:06:11.760
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Hugo Barra: Thank you.

00:06:11.760 --> 00:06:17.960
And do you know what the most exciting thing
about this stat is? It's the fact that we

00:06:17.960 --> 00:06:31.980
all did it together. 36 OEMs, 215 carriers,
and 450,000 Android developers all over the

00:06:31.980 --> 00:06:35.240
world. Thank you!
[ Applause ]

00:06:35.240 --> 00:06:47.210
&gt;&gt;Hugo Barra: There are now more than 310
Android devices in 112 countries. Talk about

00:06:47.210 --> 00:06:52.300
choice!
And the best way to actually measure this

00:06:52.300 --> 00:06:58.990
momentum is velocity. At Google I/O on this
stage last year, Vic shared with you that

00:06:58.990 --> 00:07:03.040
we were activating 100,000 Android devices
every day.

00:07:03.040 --> 00:07:12.210
By August, that number had doubled to 200,000.
Then 300,000 in December. And today, we are

00:07:12.210 --> 00:07:16.090
activating over 400,000 Android devices every
single day.

00:07:16.090 --> 00:07:24.190
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Hugo Barra: Now, there's a reason why you're

00:07:24.190 --> 00:07:30.930
all here today. It's because you write software.
And most of you write Android apps.

00:07:30.930 --> 00:07:37.199
Well, thanks to your extremely hard work,
I'm excited to announce today that we've exceeded

00:07:37.199 --> 00:07:42.300
the mark of 200,000 applications available
in Android Market.

00:07:42.300 --> 00:07:49.229
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Hugo Barra: And of course what really matters

00:07:49.229 --> 00:07:52.830
is that the quality of these applications
is phenomenal.

00:07:52.830 --> 00:07:59.479
CNN, Flixter, Fruit Ninja, Tap Tap Revenge,
Major League Baseball, Gun Brothers, Pulse,

00:07:59.479 --> 00:08:07.240
and so many more. The world's most engaging,
useful, and entertaining mobile applications

00:08:07.240 --> 00:08:13.990
are running on Android.
And the most important thing for you, Android

00:08:13.990 --> 00:08:22.451
developer, is the tremendous growth in application
downloads. Here's some data: It took the Android

00:08:22.451 --> 00:08:29.389
ecosystem almost two years to see the first
billion application installs.

00:08:29.389 --> 00:08:33.889
It then took just five months to get to the
second billion.

00:08:33.889 --> 00:08:40.490
Well, today, we're seeing one billion downloads
in less than 60 days, and a total of over

00:08:40.490 --> 00:08:47.560
four and a half billion application installs
from Android Market up until today, four and

00:08:47.560 --> 00:08:53.500
a half billion application installs.
Android Market is seeing stronger, faster

00:08:53.500 --> 00:09:01.649
growth than ever.
And that reminds me to pause and once again

00:09:01.649 --> 00:09:06.900
thank you, Android developer, for your amazing
support and hard work over the last two and

00:09:06.900 --> 00:09:12.589
a half years. You have been truly phenomenal,
and the entire ecosystem is now being rewarded.

00:09:12.589 --> 00:09:17.790
So thank you, and thank you very much.
[ Applause ]

00:09:17.790 --> 00:09:27.490
&gt;&gt;Hugo Barra: So this wraps up the section
about momentum of this keynote.

00:09:27.490 --> 00:09:32.890
And now there are two other parts: Mobile
and more.

00:09:32.890 --> 00:09:38.060
In mobile, we're going to cover the Android
platform and talk about some of the features

00:09:38.060 --> 00:09:41.540
on our road map.
We're also going to show you two exciting

00:09:41.540 --> 00:09:47.490
new services that we're announcing today.
And then we'll talk about more and give you

00:09:47.490 --> 00:09:54.500
a preview of the future, where Android is
headed as an open platform and an open ecosystem,

00:09:54.500 --> 00:10:01.779
going, let's say, well beyond the mobile phone.
I'd like to welcome two people on stage, Anand

00:10:01.779 --> 00:10:07.899
Agarwala, from the Android product team, will
drive our demos today. And to talk about Android

00:10:07.899 --> 00:10:11.640
platform, please welcome Mike Cleron, from
the Android engineering team.

00:10:11.640 --> 00:10:18.810
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Mike Cleron: Thanks, Hugo.

00:10:18.810 --> 00:10:24.480
Well, we've been busy. Over the last two and
a half years, the Android team has already

00:10:24.480 --> 00:10:29.080
shipped eight releases of the Android platform.
Today, I'm going to tell you what's coming

00:10:29.080 --> 00:10:32.810
next.
First, we're announcing an upgrade to Honeycomb,

00:10:32.810 --> 00:10:40.980
Android 3.1. We're rolling it out today, starting
with Verizon XOOM 3G customers. It's not been

00:10:40.980 --> 00:10:45.020
very long since we first launched Honeycomb,
but we've managed to get a lot of nice user

00:10:45.020 --> 00:10:50.410
enhancements into the 3.1 upgrade. Let me
show you a couple of them. First, people really

00:10:50.410 --> 00:10:55.520
like the new task switcher we introduced in
Honeycomb. You can see it here.

00:10:55.520 --> 00:10:59.260
We figured if switching between a few tasks
was good, then switching between more will

00:10:59.260 --> 00:11:05.430
be even better. We made it so you can scroll
through to see all of your most recent tasks.

00:11:05.430 --> 00:11:09.850
Remember that Android has true multitasking.
So some of these apps may really be running

00:11:09.850 --> 00:11:13.360
and some may not. But the user doesn't need
to care.

00:11:13.360 --> 00:11:18.380
This is possible only on Android, because
we're using some unique technology that automatically

00:11:18.380 --> 00:11:24.220
shuts down and restores applications transparently.
The system manages resources for you so you'll

00:11:24.220 --> 00:11:28.149
never run out of memory and you'll never be
asked to quit in order to launch something

00:11:28.149 --> 00:11:32.060
else.
Next, remember the improved widgets we introduced

00:11:32.060 --> 00:11:36.490
in Honeycomb? Let's look at the scrolling
GMail widget.

00:11:36.490 --> 00:11:39.640
That's pretty nice. But what if you get a
lot of mail?

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:42.070
Well, for that, we're taking widgets to the
next level.

00:11:42.070 --> 00:11:52.320
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Mike Cleron: So as you can see, you can

00:11:52.320 --> 00:11:56.890
now stretch widgets horizontally or vertically.
And if you're a developer and you've already

00:11:56.890 --> 00:12:01.170
created a scrolling widget for Honeycomb,
you can upgrade it to be resizable with just

00:12:01.170 --> 00:12:06.300
a few lines of XML.
In 3.1, we also put a lot of effort into upgrading

00:12:06.300 --> 00:12:11.620
Droid's USB support. Android devices can now
act as USB hosts, which means you can now

00:12:11.620 --> 00:12:13.779
do things like --
[ Applause ]

00:12:13.779 --> 00:12:20.420
&gt;&gt;Mike Cleron: Yeah.
So that means you can now do things like importing

00:12:20.420 --> 00:12:23.860
photos directly from your digital camera to
your tablet.

00:12:23.860 --> 00:12:29.190
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Mike Cleron: And because Android is now

00:12:29.190 --> 00:12:34.830
a USB host, the OS also supports a ridiculous
number of USB input devices as well, keyboards,

00:12:34.830 --> 00:12:38.379
mice, trackpads, joysticks, game controllers,
and more.

00:12:38.379 --> 00:12:46.800
[ Cheers and applause ]
&gt;&gt;Mike Cleron: So here you're about to see

00:12:46.800 --> 00:12:51.959
Anand play, or, rather, attempt to play, Cordy
using a game controller.

00:12:51.959 --> 00:12:56.680
Okay.
[ Laughter ]

00:12:56.680 --> 00:13:02.480
&gt;&gt;Mike Cleron: Okay, well, that was a brave
attempt.

00:13:02.480 --> 00:13:08.110
There's a lot more in 3.1. But let me move
on to some other platform news.

00:13:08.110 --> 00:13:12.730
It turns out that Android 3.1 is not just
for tablets. It's also coming to Google TV

00:13:12.730 --> 00:13:16.390
this summer. This is great news for Google
TV users.

00:13:16.390 --> 00:13:23.730
[ Cheers and applause ]
&gt;&gt;Mike Cleron: It's great news for Google

00:13:23.730 --> 00:13:29.040
TV users. And it gets better. Google TV will
also be getting the Android Market. So all

00:13:29.040 --> 00:13:31.010
of you developers --
[ Applause ]

00:13:31.010 --> 00:13:36.760
&gt;&gt;Mike Cleron: So all of you developers will
now be able to create apps for Google TV using

00:13:36.760 --> 00:13:41.720
exactly the same SDK that you're using for
Honeycomb. Consumers who already have a Google

00:13:41.720 --> 00:13:45.760
TV device will automatically get the upgrade
over the air. And there are new Google TV

00:13:45.760 --> 00:13:50.550
products based on 3.1 coming from Sony, Vizio,
Samsung, and Logitech.

00:13:50.550 --> 00:13:55.500
If you want to hear more about bringing your
apps to Google TV, please check out the Google

00:13:55.500 --> 00:14:01.140
TV session tomorrow here at I/O.
Let's look a little farther down the road.

00:14:01.140 --> 00:14:05.950
I'm also happy to announce the next major
Android release, Ice Cream Sandwich. And,

00:14:05.950 --> 00:14:12.759
of course, to also debut the most important
part of any release, the new logo.

00:14:12.759 --> 00:14:17.089
[ Laughter ]
[ Applause ]

00:14:17.089 --> 00:14:25.490
&gt;&gt;Mike Cleron: All right. We're targeting
a Q4 launch for Ice Cream Sandwich. And in

00:14:25.490 --> 00:14:29.050
many ways, this will be our most ambitious
release to date.

00:14:29.050 --> 00:14:31.860
Let me tell you about some of the themes behind
this release.

00:14:31.860 --> 00:14:37.570
First, choice. If I had to pick one word to
explain Android's phenomenal growth over the

00:14:37.570 --> 00:14:42.399
past year, that word would be "choice."
Consumers really like choices. And with Ice

00:14:42.399 --> 00:14:45.269
Cream Sandwich, we're going to make them really,
really happy.

00:14:45.269 --> 00:14:49.950
Here's just a small sample of the range of
devices that we've powered by Android.

00:14:49.950 --> 00:14:57.160
So we have phones in every size and shape;
phones with keyboards that slide; phones with

00:14:57.160 --> 00:15:01.769
keyboards that flip; phones with built-in
game controllers; tablets in every size from

00:15:01.769 --> 00:15:07.210
seven inches to ten inches; even tablets that
transform into laptops. And who knows what

00:15:07.210 --> 00:15:10.930
else is coming.
But in the end, we know that high-quality

00:15:10.930 --> 00:15:15.570
apps are the lifeblood of Android. So our
top priority for Ice Cream Sandwich will be

00:15:15.570 --> 00:15:21.209
to give app developers the tools they need
to deliver great experiences on all of these

00:15:21.209 --> 00:15:27.100
devices. We want one OS that runs everywhere.
Let me tell you how we're going to make that

00:15:27.100 --> 00:15:30.360
happen.
To start, we're taking all of the good stuff

00:15:30.360 --> 00:15:34.399
that we added to Honeycomb for tablets and
we'll make it available everywhere, on phones,

00:15:34.399 --> 00:15:40.380
on tablets, on everything in between.
This includes the new holographic UI, the

00:15:40.380 --> 00:15:47.670
new launcher, the new multitasking UI, richer
widgets, advanced applications, everything.

00:15:47.670 --> 00:15:52.000
Next, we're investing heavily in the application
framework. We want to insulate developers

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:56.079
from the differences between all of those
devices as much as possible.

00:15:56.079 --> 00:16:00.639
So we're adding new APIs to the framework
to help scale your UI across all these different

00:16:00.639 --> 00:16:05.089
form factors. And we're adding intelligence
to components like the action bar. They'll

00:16:05.089 --> 00:16:09.190
be able to reconfigure themselves to optimize
for the available space.

00:16:09.190 --> 00:16:13.060
We're also putting a lot of energy into our
development tools.

00:16:13.060 --> 00:16:17.260
Be sure to check out the Android tools talk
tomorrow at 3:00 for some exciting developments

00:16:17.260 --> 00:16:21.180
there.
And last, but certainly not least, it will

00:16:21.180 --> 00:16:27.200
all be open source.
[ Applause ]

00:16:27.200 --> 00:16:35.070
&gt;&gt;Mike Cleron: Now, Ice Cream Sandwich is
not just about breadth. It's about depth,

00:16:35.070 --> 00:16:37.639
too.
On Android, we're always looking to bring

00:16:37.639 --> 00:16:43.490
the latest technology to mobile devices. And
we've got some really cutting-edge stuff in

00:16:43.490 --> 00:16:44.490
the works.
Anand is going to help me demo some of the

00:16:44.490 --> 00:16:49.149
latest developments from Google's Technology
Extraction Team based in Roswell, New Mexico.

00:16:49.149 --> 00:16:52.630
[ Laughter. ]
&gt;&gt;Mike Cleron: For real.

00:16:52.630 --> 00:16:57.200
Basically, this technology can look at the
input from the camera and figure out where

00:16:57.200 --> 00:17:01.459
your head is and even where you're looking.
It runs on the GPU, so it can do all that

00:17:01.459 --> 00:17:04.799
insanely fast. It can process 500 frames a
second.

00:17:04.799 --> 00:17:09.740
So let's have some fun with that.
First, watch what happens as Anand moves his

00:17:09.740 --> 00:17:13.740
head from side to side.
Because the software knows where he's looking,

00:17:13.740 --> 00:17:17.470
it can update the 3D scene in real time to
match his perspective.

00:17:17.470 --> 00:17:26.569
[ Cheers and applause ]
&gt;&gt;Mike Cleron: Okay.

00:17:26.569 --> 00:17:33.030
How about this? We cannot only detect where
Anand's head is but we also know where his

00:17:33.030 --> 00:17:37.480
eyes, nose, and mouth are.
Now, Anand is a handsome guy, but there's

00:17:37.480 --> 00:17:40.200
always room for a little improvement. So let's
fix him up.

00:17:40.200 --> 00:17:50.640
Okay. That's not really a good look. Maybe
something in the nose area.

00:17:50.640 --> 00:17:54.340
Okay. That's pretty unfortunate.
Maybe eyes a little smaller?

00:17:54.340 --> 00:17:57.230
Wow. Okay.
[ Laughter ]

00:17:57.230 --> 00:18:02.660
&gt;&gt;Mike Cleron: I think the lesson here is
not to attempt to improve on nature.

00:18:02.660 --> 00:18:10.250
Let's move on to something more practical.
We call it virtual camera operator.

00:18:10.250 --> 00:18:14.510
Let's say Anand and Hugo are together on a
video chat. The software can actually figure

00:18:14.510 --> 00:18:18.920
out by itself who is speaking and will automatically
focus on the right person.

00:18:18.920 --> 00:18:25.940
Let's give that a try.
&gt;&gt;Anand Agarwala: Anand Agarwala So you can

00:18:25.940 --> 00:18:29.130
see here as I start talking, it zooms in smoothly
to my face.

00:18:29.130 --> 00:18:32.840
&gt;&gt;Hugo Barra: Then when I start talking after
a few seconds, the camera realizes that I'm

00:18:32.840 --> 00:18:35.421
here and it's going to zoom in on my face
automatically.

00:18:35.421 --> 00:18:37.540
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Anand Agarwala: When I start talking again,

00:18:37.540 --> 00:18:40.573
it zooms fluidly back to me with a smooth,
fluid back and forth transition.

00:18:40.573 --> 00:18:50.710
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Mike Cleron: That's pretty amazing.

00:18:50.710 --> 00:18:55.280
And note that this is not just for fun. All
of this and more will be available as developer

00:18:55.280 --> 00:18:59.340
APIs in Ice Cream Sandwich so all of you can
create great new experiences.

00:18:59.340 --> 00:19:05.169
That's just a quick peak at what's coming
in 2011 for the Android platform. We're really

00:19:05.169 --> 00:19:08.900
excited about moving Android forward and can't
wait to see what all of you will build with

00:19:08.900 --> 00:19:10.070
it.
Thanks very much.

00:19:10.070 --> 00:19:12.100
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Mike Cleron: Hugo, back to you.

00:19:12.100 --> 00:19:15.550
&gt;&gt;Hugo Barra: Thank you, Mike. Thank you,
that was great.

00:19:15.550 --> 00:19:23.299
So we had a little bit of fun with Anand.
We showed you a new dessert. And we talked

00:19:23.299 --> 00:19:29.549
about the importance of one Android OS everywhere.
We're now going to shift topics and talk about

00:19:29.549 --> 00:19:33.400
media.
Today, we're announcing a couple of new services

00:19:33.400 --> 00:19:38.230
that we think you'll really enjoy. And to
